    <node id="The purpose of the text describing various ways to clean oneself is to emphasize the importance placed on personal hygiene in this society. This relates to registering for a &quot;family&quot; and being mindful of one's social status because it suggests that once Michael is registered, he will also be expected to maintain certain standards of cleanliness and presentability as part of his new social position.&#10;&#10;In the story, the text about cleaning methods serves as an advertisement for Omniclene, a product from Kiffa that claims to work for all species and cultures. This emphasizes the diversity of species and cultures coexisting in this society, further highlighting the need for a universal standard of cleanliness that can accommodate everyone.&#10;&#10;By registering for a &quot;family,&quot; Michael will be entering a new social group with its own expectations and norms. Maintaining proper hygiene would likely be one of those expectations, as it is considered important in this society. Furthermore, the way he presents himself (including his cleanliness) may influence how others perceive his social status. Therefore, being aware of and adhering to these standards will be essential for Michael as he navigates his new social environment." />
    <node id=" Foreign atmospheres prove deleterious. Only with our mind's eye can we sail through the sky to the bright purple swamps of our Sirius.&quot;&#10; &#10; The cost of the compartment was half that of the feeding station; one credit in the slot unlocked the door. There was an advideo here, too:&#10; &#10; &quot;Friend, do you clean yourself each day? Now, let's not be evasive, for each one has his favored way. Some use an abrasive and some use oil. Some shed their skins, in a brand-new hide emerging. Some rub with grease put up in tins. For others there's deterging. Some lick themselves to take off grime. Some beat it off with rope. Some cook it away in boiling lime. Old-fashioned ones use soap. More ways there are than I recall, and each of these will differ, but the only one that works for all is Omniclene from Kiffa.&quot;&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; &quot;And now,&quot; smiled Carpenter as the two humans left the building, &quot;we must see you registered for a nice family. Nothing too ostentatious, but, on the other hand, you mustn't count credits and ally yourself beneath your station.&quot;" />
    <node id="1. Michael's comments about the Brotherhood's inclusion of both sexes and his desire to return to the safety of his own kind suggest that the Brotherhood is a place where he feels comfortable and accepted, particularly in contrast to the diverse crowd of extraterrestrial life-forms on the landing field. This reinforces the idea that Michael is not used to being around such a wide variety of alien creatures and prefers to be in the company of his own kind.&#10;2. The Sirians' melancholy howling and quote about returning to the swamps of Sirius can be seen as a reflection of their longing for their home planet and culture, similar to Michael's desire to return to the Brotherhood. It also highlights the theme of homesickness and a sense of not belonging that is present throughout the story.&#10;3. The initial question about a girl in the Brotherhood is likely rooted in the assumption that Brotherhoods are exclusive to men, which is challenged by Michael's statement that both sexes are represented in their society. However, Michael's laughter and the later conversation between him and Carpenter suggest that there may still be taboo or unconventional aspects to having a &quot;girl&quot; (presumably a romantic partner) while being a member of the Brotherhood. This further emphasizes the theme of societal norms and expectations, as well as the challenges of adapting to new environments and cultures." />
    <node id="1. Michael is anxiously considering the implications of starting a family of his own, particularly in the context of the unusual societal norms and laws on Talitha. He wants to bring his girlfriend from Earth and get married, which goes against the law on Talitha that outlaws exclusive possession of a member of the opposite sex.&#10;2. Carpenter interprets Michael's concerns as anxiety about adapting to civilized behavior patterns on Talitha, suggesting that he may not be able to fit in with the local culture and norms. He also seems to be worried about Michael's plans to keep his girlfriend exclusively for himself, which goes against the Talithan law promoting shared possession of romantic partners." />
